  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum of 30 years for more serious cases involving specific predicate crimes\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Fines up to $500,000 or double the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Potential civil monetary penalties\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential seizure of funds/property involved in laundering\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n4. Specific statutes involved:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering Crime)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary Transaction in Criminally Derived Property)\n\nActual sentencing depends on specific circumstances, amount of money involved, prior criminal history, and whether the offense was part of larger criminal enterprise.\n\nThese are general guidelines based on federal statutes. Specific case details and individual circumstances can significantly impact actual penalties.",
